- "Top 3" refers to the highest ranks based on average code complexity;
- "Average code complexity" is a measure of the complexity of the code in the commits;
- "Average added lines" is the average number of lines added in the commits.

- "Thorniest bushes" refer to commits with the highest code complexity;
- "Infested with bugs" means commits that contain bugs;
- "Roots" and "leaves" are metaphorical references to the commit ID and author ID, respectively;
- "How hard they are to tend" refers to the maintainability index.

- 'Higher complexity' refers to commits with entropy greater than the average entropy of all commits;
- 'John Doe' is the name of the author;
- 'My Repository' is the name of the repository.

- "peak of the mountain of changes" refers to the maximum total lines changed in a single commit;
- "total lines altered" includes the sum of added lines, deleted lines, and changed lines;
- "vast landscape of code modifications" represents the entire set of commits in the database.

- The quality score is calculated as the maintainability index plus the average of the inverse probabilities of introducing a bug (1 - glm_probability and 1 - rf_probability);
- The `PERCENT_RANK()` function ranks the commits in descending order of the quality score;
- The most recent commit is identified by the highest commit ID.

- 'masterpieces' refers to commits;
- 'seasoned artisans' refers to authors whose bio contains the word 'experienced';
- 'logged more than five years of experience' refers to `exp > 5`.

- 'Higher likelihood of commits introducing bugs' means `glm_probability > 0.5`;
- 'Average code complexity' is calculated as the mean of `code_complexity` for commits in the repository;
- 'Average bug probability' is calculated as the mean of `glm_probability` for commits in the repository.

- A "top contributor" is someone with a high number of commits in the project;
- "Bug-containing commits" are commits that have been marked as containing bugs;
- "Distinct issues" are unique issues that have been fixed by the commits.

- 'High number' refers to more than 50 bug fix commits;
- 'Complex' is defined by an average complexity rank greater than 10;
- 'Less maintainable' is defined by an average maintainability rank greater than 5.

- "shining star" refers to the top contributor;
- "lit up the repository" refers to having the highest commit count;
- "most activity" refers to the repository with the highest commit count.

- "gardeners" refer to the authors who made the commits;
- "plots" refer to the repositories where the commits were made;
- "weeds" refer to commits that contain bugs and are linked to issues;
- "growth" refers to the number of lines added in the commits.

- "Branches of a tree" refers to the hierarchical structure of commits in a repository;
- "Rich history of more than 100 commits" means repositories that have more than 100 commits;
- "Complexity of the code is high" is represented by a code complexity greater than 0.5;
- "Maintainability is low" is represented by a maintainability index less than 50.

- "Code complexity" is a measure of the intricacy of the code, often indicating the difficulty of understanding or maintaining it;
- "Maintainability index" is a metric that indicates how easy it is to maintain the code, with higher values suggesting better maintainability;
- "Thrive" in this context means that the repository has a positive average for both code complexity and maintainability index.

- High probability is defined as a glm_probability or rf_probability greater than 0.5;
- The `exp` column represents the experience of the developer;
- The glm and rf models are used to predict the likelihood of a commit introducing a bug.

- Experienced developers are those with an experience level greater than 5;
- Linked commits are those associated with issues;
- Code complexity is a measure of the intricacy of the code.
